t on it, though the smaller wording is not fully readable at this distance. He lowers it again, remaining calm and businesslike against a plain, softly lit background.\n\nA large document then fills the view: a “WESTERN UNION TELEGRAPHIC MONEY ORDER” form lying on a wooden surface. The top line clearly names the service, and below it, large text reads “MONEY-BY-WIRE:”. Small boxed messages appear near the top corners, but they are too small to read clearly. The blank space beneath “MONEY-BY-WIRE:” is then filled with bold typed lines: “ANY AMOUNT,” “ANYWHERE,” and “ANY TIME OF THE DAY OR NIGHT.” The form presents the service in a clear, official-looking layout, like a printed financial document.\n\nThe view changes to a countertop demonstration beside a prominent rectangular sign on a stand. The sign reads “WESTERN UNION” in large letters, with “Everywhere” written below in a script style. Only the arms and torso of a person behind the counter are visible; the person wears a light shirt with sleeves rolled up and a dark apron or skirt. On the counter are a sheet of paper, a small card, and a stack of paper money. The person’s hands handle bills and small slips, placing and arranging them next to the Western Union sign. The stack of money grows as bills are laid down in a neat pile, while the paper form remains nearby on the tabletop. The actions visually suggest processing a money order or preparing a cash payment.\n\nAnother hand, entering from the lower left and wearing a dark suit sleeve with a light cuff, reaches toward the stack of bills. This hand gathers the money from the counter, then works briefly with a small dark object near the paperwork, as if completing or marking the transaction. The form is then lifted from the counter and held up.\n\nA close view of the raised document shows the top reading “WESTERN UNION TELEGRAPHIC MONEY ORDER.” In large typed lines, the message on the form reads: “ENJOY YOURSELF — ALL WELL AT HOME. SEE YOU IN A FEW DAYS.” At the